cs.LO, cs.AI, cs.GT, cs.DS, cs.PL

This paper deals with a logical formalism for reasoning about strategies in multi-agent concurrent games, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of several subfields of computer science, including logic (cs.LO), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), game theory (cs.GT), and programming languages (cs.PL). The paper's focus on the decidability of a sublogic of Strategy Logic suggests that it is more likely to be classified under cs.LO, but its relevance to multi-agent systems and game theory also make cs.AI and cs.GT likely categories. The mention of model-checking and satisfiability problems may also indicate a connection to computational complexity and algorithms, which could place the paper in cs.DS as well.
